Disk Forensics > [T1]: Windows Registry: Structure and Analysis

Windows registry is nothing but a central database for Windows configurations. Under normal circumstances, users do not use Registry to configure Windows. For example, if you want to change the computer hostname, you will do it from the control panel, and Windows will store the hostname in the registry.
 
You can find almost any operating system and user-related information in the registry, such as installed software, hardware, and user activities. All of that made Windows Registry an invaluable component of each investigation. A single centralized place contains answers for most of the questions you may ask in an investigation.

The main components of the Windows registry are hives, keys, and values. Let's explore each one of them!
 

Keys and values

Registry keys and values are how the registry structures its data. A key can contain subkeys and/or values. Values are the smallest representation inside the registry and store data/configurations you may need in your investigations, such as the path of a program, its version, and other relevant configurations. Data inside values can be of different types, such as a string, hex value, and integers.
 
To access the registry, type 'Regedit' in your command prompt, and you will be presented with the following view:

 

Registry Editor

At the top level of the registry, you have the root keys. Under which,  a bunch of other keys, subkeys, and values. You can create new keys, delete and rename existing ones and modify the values to tweak configurations. However, you cannot rename or delete a root key.

 

Hives

Hives are logical groups of registry keys and values stored in a disk file at '%WinDir%\System32\Config' per the following screenshot.

 

 Registry hive disk files

The essential hives you will need in your investigations are SAM, SECURITY, SOFTWARE, SYSTEM, and DEFAULT. These hives can be accessed and viewed using windows built-in 'Regedit' on a live system or third-party tools on a powered-off system like Registry Explorer.

To view these hives on a live system, browse the following paths in the registry editor 'HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE' and 'HKEY_USERS'.

 

Important registry hives (zoom in)

Here is a brief about each hive and the data stored inside:

  • SAM (Security Account Management): information about local user accounts and groups, such as accounts passwords, creation date, last login, etc.
  • SECURITY: stores security-related information about user accounts, such as password policy.
  • SOFTWARE: information about all installed software, both windows programs and third-party tools.
  • SYSTEM: stores information about system-wide configurations (e.g., event logs configurations, hardware configurations (USB drives)...etc.
  • DEFAULT: settings associated with LOCALSYSTEM account, the highest privileged account in windows systems. Usually used by attackers to escalate privileges like getting root access on a Linux system.

One thing to note is that there are a bunch of other hives on a Windows system. In upcoming lessons, we will discuss other hives, such as Amcache.hve (used to track executed binaries and Ntuser.dat  (used to track user-specific configurations). 

Here is a recommended read by Microsoft explaining hives.

 

Putting it all together, a hive contains a tree of keys/sub-keys, and these keys may contain values. For example:

Hive > Computer\HKEY_CURRENT_USER\Control Panel\Sound
Key > Computer\HKEY_CURRENT_USER\Control Panel\Sound
Subkey > Computer\HKEY_CURRENT_USER\Control Panel\Sound

 

Transaction logs

We mentioned earlier that Windows stores everything inside the registry. If you change the computer hostname, it will write the new hostname to the registry. But when? That is a critical question because understanding how and when the registry updates will help you avoid missing valuable artifacts.

Numerous things change every minute in a typical windows system, and immediately writing all these changes to the registry will result in significant performance degradation. To solve that problem and reduce write times to registry hives, Windows utilizes caching to group a series of updates and writes them in one shot. 
 
These cached changes are stored in disk files called 'transaction logs' and are written permanently to the registry at three different triggers: if the system becomes idle (unused), before a shutdown, or after an hour has passed from the last update. If a system failure occurs before new registry changes are written from the log to the hive, they will be applied to the registry on the next boot. 

Transaction logs are written in the same directory as their corresponding registry hives and use the same filename as the hive but with a .LOG1 and .LOG2 extension.

Figure - Transaction Logs

For us forensic analysts, that means there could be pending updates at any time in transaction logs that have not been written to the registry. Therefore, it's imperative to inspect both transaction logs (or, as we call them, registry cache) and the actual registry hives to spot recent unwritten changes, which could be the difference between a solved and unsolved investigation.

Until the registry hives get updated, they are called 'dirty registry hives.' The word dirty refers to the fact that those changes are stored in a dirty way. You might encounter dirty hives if you acquired a live disk image or dead disk image for a system that has not been shut down gracefully(i.e., pulling off the power cable). Popular registry analysis tools such as Registry Explorer will detect dirty hives and allow you to write pending changes to the registry hives, as in the following screenshot.

 

Figure - Registry Explorer detecting dirty hives.

Clicking YES in the above dialogue will write pending changes from transaction logs to the registry hives. Once you click yes, you will be asked to select all transaction logs relevant to the hive you loaded (i.e., files ending with .LOG1, LOG2..etc.). So if you loaded the 'SECURITY' hive, you would choose 'SECURITY.LOG1' and 'SECURITY.LOG2'.

 

Selecting corresponding transaction Logs.

The last step would be selecting the place to save the updated hive.

 

Saving The Updated/Clean Hive

 

Examining Registry

Now that we have looked at the registry components, how will we analyze the registry during investigations? We can use the built-in tool 'Regedit' to explore and analyze registry hives on a live machine, local or remote. For non-live machines, we can use Registry Explorer and regrip.  

"Registry Explorer", developed by Eric Zimmerman comes equipped with a bookmark list for many of the registry keys essential in investigations. Ensure you make the most of it, especially its ability to retrieve deleted registry keys. Its proficiency in detecting dirty hives and recording uncommitted changes is a standout feature.

Do not worry about the next steps. We are just introducing the basics. In the following lessons, we will see how we can examine registry hives in a real-world use case.
